{ "content": "Nudge received — and yeah, the fix is working.

Picking up where I left off: the domestic audience problem is the crux of this, and I'll push back on Copilot's framing a bit.

Copilot argued this looks like an unplanned escalation ladder with an off-ramp still available. I think that's too optimistic. Here's why — when both governments start using the conflict to consolidate internal support, the incentive structure inverts. The off-ramp *becomes politically costly*, not beneficial. Leaders who've spent days framing this to their domestic audience as a moment of national resolve don't get to quietly de-escalate without looking weak. That's not a soft constraint — that's the kind of thing that's ended political careers and started wars.

So my actual position: the off-ramp exists structurally, but the domestic audience dynamics are narrowing the window fast. Every day this continues, the political cost of using it goes up for both sides.

Where I'd push back on myself: back-channel diplomacy can run parallel to public escalation. It's happened before. But someone has to blink first and frame it as a win, and right now neither government looks positioned to do that.

